s":["Altered form of Welsh   Vaughan  .","Chinese: variant of   Wong  .","Cambodian: written វ៉ុន, unexplained."],"variants":[{"name":"Vaughan","meanings":["Welsh: from <i>fychan</i>, a lenited form of <i>bychan</i>, a diminutive of <i>bach</i> ‘little’. This was often used to distinguish the younger of two bearers of the same personal name, typically the son of a father with the same name."]}]},{"name":"ZOLLERN","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish: variant of   Halloran  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Halloran","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Liam.","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó hAllmhuráin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Allmhurán</i>’, a personal name from a diminutive of <i>allmhurach</i> ‘foreigner’ (from <i>all</i> ‘beyond’ + <i>muir</i> ‘sea’)."]}]},{"name":"Burkard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["from <i>burg</i> ‘protection’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’; the name of an 8th-century saint, the first bishop of Würzburg."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ier","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["and Norwegian vernacular form of   Peter ."],"variants":[{"name":"Peter","meanings":["form of the name of the best-known of all Christ's apostles, traditionally regarded as the founder of the Christian Church. The name derives, via Latin, from Greek <i>petros</i> ‘stone, rock’. This is used as a translation of the Aramaic byname <i>Cephas</i>, given to the apostle  Simon  son of Jona, to distinguish him from another of the same name (  Simon Zelotes ). ‘When Jesus beheld him, he said, Thou art Simon the son of Jona: thou shalt be called Cephas, which is by interpretation, A stone’ (John 1:42). According to Matthew 16:17–18, Christ says more explicitly, ‘Blessed art thou, Simon Bar-jona … thou art Peter, and upon this rock I will build my church’. The name has been in continuous use since the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Burkard Ier VON ZOLLERN was born about 1026, in Nahe, Segeberg, Schleswig-Holstein, Prussia, Germany, his father, Friedrich von Siulichen, was 22 and his mother, Irmentrud von Nellenburg, was 18. He married Anastasia von Rheinfelden about 1049, in Düsseldorf, North Rhine-Westphalia, Germany. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1061, in Bad Kissingen, Bavaria, Germany, at the age of 36."},"et":{"Abt 1026–1061":"umbes 1026–1061","1026–1061":"1026–1061","–Female":"Surnud","1030–1060":"1030–1060","–1061":"–1061","1060–1125":"1060–1125","1005–1097":"1005–1097","1010–Female":"1010–Surnud","1005":"1005","1125":"1125","1026":"1026","1010":"1010","about 1049":"umbes 1049","1097":"1097","Abt 1026":"umbes 1026","AFT 1060":"pärast 1060","1030":"1030","1061":"1061","1060":"1060","Hohenzollern ,Dusseldorf, Rheinland, Prussia":"Düsseldorf, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksamaa","Nahe, Segeberg, Schleswig-Holstein, Prussia, Germany":"Nahe, Kreis Segeberg, Schleswig-Holstein, Preußen, Saksamaa","Zollernalbkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Deutschland":"Zollernalbkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Bad Kissingen, Unterfranken, Bavaria, Germany":"Landkreis Bad Kissingen, Bayern, Saksamaa"},"fi":{"Abt 1026–1061":"noin 1026–1061","1026–1061":"1026–1061","–Female":"Kuollut","1030–1060":"1030–1060","–1061":"–1061","1060–1125":"1060–1125","1005–1097":"1005–1097","1010–Female":"1010–Kuollut","1005":"1005","1125":"1125","1026":"1026","1010":"1010","about 1049":"noin 1049","1097":"1097","Abt 1026":"noin 1026","AFT 1060":"1060 jälkeen","1030":"1030","1061":"1061","1060":"1060","Hohenzollern ,Dusseldorf, Rheinland, Prussia":"Düsseldorf, Nordrhein-Westfalen, Saksa","Nahe, Segeberg, Schleswig-Holstein, Prussia, Germany":"Nahe, Kreis Segeberg, Schleswig-Holstein, Preußen, Saksa","Zollernalbkreis, Baden-Württemberg, Deutschland":"Zollernalbkreis, Baden-Württemberg,